{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:55:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:55:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17191"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69302"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9881"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54755"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7616"},{"type":"tags","id":"10697"},{"type":"tags","id":"10699"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23201"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69302"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDNA contains regulatory elements that control gene expression. These elements include promoters, which assist in initiating transcription, and enhancers, which alter the level of gene expression.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the key characteristics of enhancer elements?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Must be located within 100 base pairs of the promoter","Work only in the same orientation as the gene","Require direct contact with RNA polymerase","Function only when positioned upstream of genes","Increase transcription regardless of orientation or distance"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEnhancers are regulatory DNA sequences that \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease transcription regardless of orientation or distance\u003C/strong\u003E from target genes. They bind specific transcription factors which then interact with transcriptional machinery at the promoter through DNA looping mechanisms. This allows enhancers to influence gene expression even when separated from the promoter by thousands of base pairs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect statements can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMust be located within 100 base pairs of the promoter\u003C/strong\u003E - Enhancers commonly function from distances of thousands or even hundreds of thousands of base pairs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunction only when positioned upstream of genes\u003C/strong\u003E - Enhancers can be found upstream, downstream, or within introns of their target genes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequire direct contact with RNA polymerase\u003C/strong\u003E - Enhancers act through transcription factors and mediator proteins rather than direct interaction with RNA polymerase\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWork only in the same orientation as the gene\u003C/strong\u003E - Enhancer function is independent of their orientation relative to the gene\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe flexibility in positioning and orientation of enhancers allows for complex patterns of gene regulation during development and in response to cellular signals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Enhancers are DNA sequences that increase gene transcription by binding transcription factors, even when located far from the promoter.","Enhancers function independently of orientation and can be located upstream, downstream, or within introns of a regulated gene.","DNA looping allows enhancers to interact with promoters despite being separated by large distances."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54755"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54755"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T18:50:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T18:51:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9881"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69302"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}}